{
  "action_id": "54",
  "action_title": "Rear and manage populations of solitary bees",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nSeveral species of solitary bee in the family Megachilidae are reared and managed commercially as pollinators, mostly for the forage crop alfalfa, or fruit trees.\u00a0These species readily nest in drilled wooden blocks, or stacked grooved boards of wood or polystyrene. Parasites and pathogens can be problematic and a number of control methods have been developed. Rearing methods have been investigated for two other species not yet commercially managed and one replicated trial shows that temperature regimes are important to survival. If rearing for conservation purposes is to be attempted, we would recommend a systematic review of these methods.\nThree management trials with megachilids not commercially managed in the USA or Poland, and a review of studies of managed species, found that local populations can increase up to six-fold in one year under management if conditions are good and plentiful floral resources are provided.\nTwo replicated trials have reared solitary bees on artificial diets. One found high larval mortality in Osmia cornuta reared on artificial pollen-based diets, including honey bee-collected pollen. The other found Megachile rotundata could be reared on an artificial diet based on honey bee-collected pollen, but bees reared on synthetic pollen substitutes either died or had low pre-pupal weight."
}

{
  "query": "In the USA, what factors have been shown to affect the success of artificial nesting sites for solitary bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "A study in the USA indicated that providing nest boxes for solitary bees, specifically species of Osmia, led to an increase in the estimated number of foraging bees in blueberry fields over a three-year period (47). For foraging resources, studies have shown that nest boxes need to be within 150 to 600 meters of these resources (47, 80), and providing plentiful floral resources can lead to population increases (54). The design and material of the nest box are also factors; one trial demonstrated that reed stem and wooden grooved-board nest boxes produced a higher number of bees per nest compared to other designs like plastic-lined holes or tubes, which suffered from issues with parasitism or mould (47). Another trial found that nests in cardboard straws placed within drilled wooden holes were more productive than those in grooved wooden boards (47). Parasites and pathogens can be an issue, with mortality rates ranging from 13% to 56% in some studies (47, 54). A trial in California, USA, noted that introduced species, such as the European earwig and European leafcutter bee, occupied nest boxes, sometimes more frequently than native bees (47). Additionally, temperature has been found to be an important factor for survival in reared populations (54). Repeated provision of nest boxes at a site can double the number of occupied nests over three years (47).",
  "action_ids": [
    "47",
    "54",
    "80"
  ]
}

